reviews.text:
I thought this was going to be a disaster going in, but it really works! Why would I think that? Lots of reasons! &#xD;
&#xD;
Ginger Peach, I didn’t think would have enough peach at 1% for a bellini profile. Certainly not enough to overcome all the citrus, which was another concern. Between the blood orange and the lemons I thought this is going to come across way too citrusy. But that citrus really just uplifts the peach and makes the champagne more of a dry champagne, though there is a little kick of sweet lemon at the tail end. Second, Golden Syrup and CAP Gingerbread. Golden syrup seemed a little too rich, almost buttery, and I was thinking that combined with the creamy cream-soda type base of the Ginger Peach it would just be a disaster. But it isn’t. It isn’t too rich and creamy at all, it has a bubbly champagne feel to it that I think is enhanced by the spice. And CAP Gingerbread is a bakery flavor, why that of all the gingers to choose from? It made no sense. But by some magic, the bakery is washed out and it really comes across like ginger syrup in a drink with a nice spicy kick. This is awesome stuff. It’s a bit out there in terms of profile but if it’s a profile that interests you, you should definitely give it a try. We’re coming up on Christmas now and it’s perfect for that sort of festive spirit. I might try it with a little less of the VT Sour Lemon lemon next time because I think that’s probably where the lingering lemon finish is coming from, but overall this is a very nice and very interesting and fun recipe. &#xD;
